[Student "S"]
{One school of thought says to open 2\C with a hand that is within one trick of game, even though the point count is below 22.

Another school of thought says to go ahead and bid the game, hoping to keep the opponents away from any competition.

Today you take the second and bid 4\H.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \DQ.

<b>East plays 4\H. South leads the \DQ.</b>

Losers: \S 3 : \H 0 : \D 0 : \C 1 : Total = 4

You are going to lose the \C for sure, so you need to find a way to hold the \S losers to 2. The obvious possibility is for South to hold the \SA and you lead through him to make the \SK a winner. That's a 50% possibility.

But you can improve on that a little bit. If South holds both the \S Q J you could make a deep finesse of dummy's \ST and North would have to play his \SA to win the trick. And if it didn't work and North won with a lesser \S you would still have time to play toward the \SK.

Win the \D, pull trumps, lead the \S3 to dummy's \ST. 

You can see that the deep finesse would indeed force North's \SA. However, South played his \SQ to the trick, forcing you to go up with dummy's \SK, which was taken by North's \SA. 

You must modify the Plan a little bit. Now your only hope is that South still holds the \SJ. So you win the next trick in your hand and lead a \S toward dummy's \ST. This time South is caught. He plays the \SJ hoping you had a doubleton, but you still have a \S to get to the now high \ST.}
[Play "W"]DQ

